User Guide for MAMID
(monitor and manger for in memory databases)



Content:
1. General Infromation
2. Overview view
3. Problems view
4. Slaves view
5. Riskgroups view
6. Replica Sets view

---

Overview:

The overview shows any problems that recetnly occured, as well as the general states of the slaves. 

 - Problems:
	The three most recent problems will appear in the overview. 
	
	
 - Slave State:
	A pie diagram of the slaves states. Slaves can have one of four states:
		1. Active (green)
			Slaves can be set to active (Slaves view).
			A slave working as planned. Active slaves will 				be monitored. If a problem occures in an active  				slave, it will be set to problematic.
		2. Maintenance(blue)
			Slaves can be set to maintenance mode (Slaves view).
			A slave in maintenance mode will not be monitored and no new mogod 				instances will be spawned. Existing mogods will be left untouched.
		3. Disabled (grey)
			Slaves can be set to disabled (Slaves view).
		4. Problematic (red)
			If a proplem occures in a slave, it will be set to problematic. This 				happens automaticly.
			
	
---

Problems:

Problems can occur in slaves and replica sets. Every problem shown will have a shortcut to the affected slave/replicaset.
Problems are ordered chronological.

---

Slaves:

Slaves are ordered by their state.

 - Creating a slave:
	1. Click the Button in the top right corner.
	2. Hostname: a name to identify the slave
	3. Slave port
	4. Mongod port range
	5. Persistent storage: Choose this option if the ... has and the slave is meant to 		   use persistent storage
	

